the complaint directly to the hospital executive board","Request she put all concerns in writing before taking any action","Notify the Australian Health Practitioner Regulation Agency immediately","Acknowledge her right to complain and work towards local resolution","Transfer her care to another medical team"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate initial response is to \u003Cstrong\u003Eacknowledge her right to complain and work towards local resolution\u003C/strong\u003E. This approach demonstrates respect for patient autonomy while attempting to address concerns at the earliest opportunity and most appropriate level.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect responses are inappropriate because:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERefer the complaint directly to the hospital executive board\u003C/strong\u003E - This bypasses local resolution processes which should be attempted first\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERequest she put all concerns in writing before taking any action\u003C/strong\u003E - While written documentation may be helpful, delaying any response until this occurs is not patient-centred and may escalate tensions\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENotify the Australian Health Practitioner Regulation Agency immediately\u003C/strong\u003E - This is a significant escalation and inappropriate for an initial response to a communication complaint that should first be managed locally\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransfer her care to another medical team\u003C/strong\u003E - This is premature and may be seen as avoiding the issue. Transfer should only occur if attempts at resolution fail or if the therapeutic relationship is irreparably damaged\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGood complaint handling involves acknowledging the complaint, working towards local resolution where possible, providing prompt and constructive responses, ensuring ongoing care is not adversely affected, and using the experience as an opportunity for reflection and improvement.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["When receiving patient complaints, doctors must acknowledge the right to complain and work towards local resolution where possible.","Patient complaints should be handled promptly, openly and constructively with appropriate explanations and apologies.","Complaints must not adversely affect patient care and should be viewed as opportunities for reflection and improvement."],"references":["Medical Board of Australia. Good medical practice: a code of conduct for doctors in Australia [online]. 2020 [Cited 2025 Jan 15]. Available at: https://www.medicalboard.gov.au/codes-guidelines-policies/code-of-conduct.aspx."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64930"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18836"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64930"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-15T11:45:49+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-15T11:46:49+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11569"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79626"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the